    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/task_003/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The 'categorate()' function will then take the input library (saved as a '.CSV') and compare every chemical of interest to the chemicals in each user-defined 'chemical category,' returning two additional data frames\u2014(1) whether it has a strong (Tanimoto similarity greater than 0.95) or moderate (greater than 0.85) structural match with any of the chemicals in each group; and, (2) for strong matches, the name of a chemical that it was most similar to. It performs these comparisons using the 'fmcsBatch()' function from the R package fmcsR.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper describes categorate() function and its structural matching capability, but the specific test compounds mentioned in the card (Ethyl hexanoate and isobutyl hexanoate) are not explicitly tested together in the passages. Ethyl hexanoate is mentioned as a test standard [passage 6], but isobutyl hexanoate is not mentioned. The function does perform structural similarity matching as described, but the specific research question about these two compounds is not directly addressed in the passages.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_003",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Does the categorate() function correctly identify structurally similar compounds (Ethyl hexanoate and isobutyl hexanoate) when applied under structural-match conditions using a restricted chemical library?",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:25:04.655359+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/task_003/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The 'categorate()' function will then take the input library (saved as a '.CSV') and compare every chemical of interest to the chemicals in each user-defined 'chemical category,' returning two additional data frames\u2014(1) whether it has a strong (Tanimoto similarity greater than 0.95) or moderate (greater than 0.85) structural match with any of the chemicals in each group; and, (2) for strong matches, the name of a chemical that it was most similar to.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper describes categorate() returning data frames with match information (strong/moderate/no match based on Tanimoto thresholds), but does not explicitly describe the output format using 'No, ~, Yes' notation or 'CMP identifier' naming convention. The function returns whether matches exist and names of matched chemicals, but the specific output structure claimed in the card is not verbatim in the passages.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_003",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "expected_outputs",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Structural match results dataframe showing query chemicals vs. type categories with match outcome (No, ~, Yes) and matched compound identifier (e.g., CMP1, CMP2)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:25:04.655359+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/task_003/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "for strong matches, the name of a chemical that it was most similar to",
      "asbval:note": "The paper states categorate() returns 'the name of a chemical that it was most similar to' for strong matches, which is functionally equivalent to a 'best compound match mapping.' However, the specific format (CMP identifier notation) is not mentioned in the passages.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_003",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "expected_outputs",
