    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/chemical-identifier-verification/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "After identifying perfect matches (i.e., those with high match factors and the same chemical names) the algorithm looks again through each sample for instances where the top 2 published m/z values for the tentative identity are the same as the query chemicals of interest... The m/z values within retention time windows generated by the input data must be similar enough that the chemical fragments are practically and theoretically identical.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper explicitly describes the mzExacto algorithm using retention time windows, m/z matching, and match factors to identify query chemicals.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "chemical-identifier-verification",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Verify that a set of query chemicals can be correctly retrieved and identified from GC-MS data using retention time, m/z peaks, and match factor thresholds.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:27:40.185322+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/chemical-identifier-verification/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "mzExacto() takes the output from spreadOut() along with the list of chemical names, and returns a single data frame containing their optimal retention time, exact mass, best identified match factor, and aggregated component area across samples in which it occurs",
      "asbval:note": "The paper confirms that mzExacto extracts exactly these metadata fields from preprocessed data.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "chemical-identifier-verification",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "This skill validates whether mass spectrometry search algorithms accurately extract compound-specific metadata (exact mass, retention time, match factor, area) from preprocessed spectral dictionaries.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:27:40.185322+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/chemical-identifier-verification/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To showcase the utility and validity of our package for GC -MS workflows, we analyzed two datasets\u2013one containing a set of known standards pipetted in known quantities across three samples (low, medium, and high concentrations)... Peak areas calculated by uafR for the set of standards correlated with the volume of the standards injected, with R2 values ranging from 0.8273 to 0.9998",
      "asbval:note": "The paper demonstrates exactly this use case: validating retrieval of known compound metadata using standards.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "chemical-identifier-verification",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "When you have a list of chemically known compounds and need to validate that an MS processing pipeline (e.g., mzExacto) correctly retrieves their characteristic m/z, retention time, match factor, and area values from GC-MS data.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:27:40.185322+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/chemical-identifier-verification/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The first dataset on which uafR functions were tested was a series of standards including, ethyl hexanoate... methyl salicylate... octanal... and undecane... collected on an Agilent 7890b gas chromatograph (GC)... Peak areas calculated by uafR for the set of standards correlated with the volume of the standards injected, with R2 values ranging from 0.8273 to 0.9998",
      "asbval:note": "The paper uses these exact four compounds as test standards. Match factor thresholds are discussed in the paper (e.g., '>75% Match Factor', '>88.9 Match Factor').",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "chemical-identifier-verification",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Typical scenario: you have 4 standard solutions with known compound identities (e.g., Ethyl hexanoate, Methyl salicylate, Octanal, Undecane) and want to confirm the pipeline extracts matching rows across all samples with consistent match factors \u226565 and correct retention time ord",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:27:40.185322+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/chemical-identifier-verification/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The first function for GC -MS data is 'spreadOut().' Running this function on properly formatted GC -MS input will automatically prepare the data for the next steps in the processing pipeline. Briefly, the function takes every recorded data point for every treatment and expands it in large database formats with unique identifiers assigned for each data point... the function also communicates with online databases to download relevant information about every tentative compound.",
      "asbval:note": "spreadOut is confirmed as the preprocessing function that creates the data structure for downstream analysis.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "chemical-identifier-verification",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "spreadOut: Preprocesses raw GC-MS CSV into an advanced dictionary structure suitable for chemical searching; aggregates samples by retention time and published m/z peaks",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:27:40.185322+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
