      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/chemical-match-score-interpretation/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The next step in the GC-MS workflow will depend on the type of analysis the user is performing... Another approach could include subsetting with output from the function 'categorate().' This function also uses PubChem to communicate with online databases and generate categorically, structurally, and chemically identifying information for every published chemical in the dataset... After the categorical information is collected, the function generates substructure data for the chemicals to also be subsetted by common functional groups. This information is generated using the 'read.SDFset()' function from another R package called ChemmineR... The 'categorate()' function will then take the input library (saved as a '.CSV') and compare every chemical of interest to the chemicals in each user-defined 'chemical category,' returning two additional data frames\u2014(1) whether it has a strong (Tanimoto similarity greater than 0.95) or moderate (greater than 0.85) structural match with any of the chemicals in each group; and, (2) for strong matches, the name of a chemical that it was most similar to.",
      "asbval:note": "categorate() is confirmed to orchestrate structural matching and return match scores and group assignments. However, the paper does not explicitly name the output dataframe as 'BestChemMatch'\u2014it refers to 'two additional data frames' without naming them. The function does wrap ChemmineR and fmcsR as claimed.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "chemical-match-score-interpretation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "categorate - Orchestrates structural matching workflow; wraps ChemmineR/fmcsR/webchem and outputs BestChemMatch dataframe with match scores and group assignments",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:27:55.706963+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/chemical-match-score-interpretation/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Subsetting of information generated with 'categorate()' is easily done using the function\u2013'exactoThese().' Users can specify which set of information they would like to subset and indicate desired criteria the chemicals should meet.",
      "asbval:note": "exactoThese() is confirmed to filter categorate() output by user-specified criteria. The paper does not explicitly list all properties (MW, Rings, Groups, Atoms) in the exactoThese() description, but these are confirmed as outputs from categorate().",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "chemical-match-score-interpretation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "exactoThese - Filters categorate() output by match scores, molecular properties (MW, Rings, Groups, Atoms), or database presence for downstream subsetting",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:27:55.706963+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/chemical-match-score-interpretation/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To address these barriers in the use of GC -MS data, we developed an R package that takes the raw, aggregated chemical identifications generated from a user-selected peak detection software... The package here comes after the initial processing of samples and communicates with public chemistry utilities (including PubChem and the National Cancer Institute) to sort and process the aggregated set of all tentatively identified molecules using underlying m/z (mass/charge of chemical fragments) ratio data and automatically interpret close matches across samples.",
      "asbval:note": "Scope is consistent with paper's description of using GC-MS identifications and verifying against reference libraries.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "chemical-match-score-interpretation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "When you have query chemicals identified by GC-MS (with Match.Factor values) and need to verify structural similarity against a reference chemical library to confirm compound identity or detect structural analogs",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:27:55.706963+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/chemical-match-score-interpretation/007",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "After the categorical information is collected, the function generates substructure data for the chemicals to also be subsetted by common functional groups. This information is generated using the 'read.SDFset()' function from another R package called ChemmineR [33]. This package is a dependency that is installed with uafR and is core to the cheminformatics methods deployed. The substructure information generated using ChemmineR includes the number of rings, all subgroups (e.g., R-COH, R-COOH, etc.) and their counts, all atoms (e.g., C, N, S, As, etc.) and their counts, and the number of charges for every chemical with published structural data (or canonical SMILES from CACTUS) on PubChem.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper explicitly describes subsetting by functional groups, rings, and atoms\u2014all mentioned in the scope claim.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "chemical-match-score-interpretation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Apply this skill when a compound name alone is insufficient and you require quantified structural evidence\u2014especially when screening for specific functional groups, molecular weight ranges, or ring structures within a library.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:27:55.706963+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/chemical-name-normalization-and-publish-database-integration/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "the function converts the chemical names into PubChem compound identifiers (CIDs) using the \"get_cid()\" function from the R package webchem. For published chemicals, this information includes exact mass, m/z histograms, and every name it has.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms PubChem integration for exact mass and chemical identifiers via webchem, but does NOT mention ChemSpider. ChemSpider is not referenced anywhere in the passages. Retention time enrichment from external databases is not explicitly described; the paper focuses on retention time windows derived from input data structure, not external database lookup.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "chemical-name-normalization-and-publish-database-integration",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Normalize chemical compound names from GC-MS output and enrich them with standardized metadata (exact mass, retention time, fragment patterns, literature references) from PubChem, ChemSpider, and other curated databases.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:28:17.596843+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/chemical-name-normalization-and-publish-database-integration/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To address these barriers in the use of GC -MS data, we developed an R package that takes the raw, aggregated chemical identifications generated from a user-selected peak detection software. In this study, we used Agilent's Unknowns Analysis software to identify peaks with their deconvolution algorithm and match m/z spectra to a locally installed NIST library",
      "asbval:note": "Confirmed: uafR processes output from Agilent Unknowns Analysis and maps tentative identities to canonical forms via PubChem.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "chemical-name-normalization-and-publish-database-integration",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "This skill ensures that tentatively identified compounds from Agilent Unknowns Analysis are mapped to canonical identities",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:28:17.596843+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/chemical-name-normalization-and-publish-database-integration/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "For the chemical structure processing, our package utilizes Tanimoto similarity, a commonly used and rigorously tested metric for physicochemical comparisons. The substructure information generated using ChemmineR includes the number of rings, all subgroups (e.g., R-COH, R-COOH, etc.) and their counts, all atoms (e.g., C, N, S, As, etc.) and their counts, and the number of charges for every chemical with published structural data",
      "asbval:note": "ChemmineR is explicitly used for structure parsing and property calculation (rings, subgroups, atoms, charges).",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "chemical-name-normalization-and-publish-database-integration",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "ChemmineR \u2014 Cheminformatics toolkit providing structure parsing, similarity metrics, and property calculation",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
