      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:28:17.596843+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/chemical-name-normalization-and-publish-database-integration/012",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The first function for GC -MS data is \"spreadOut()\". Running this function on properly formatted GC -MS input will automatically prepare the data for the next steps in the processing pipeline.",
      "asbval:note": "spreadOut() is confirmed as the initial data structuring function.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "chemical-name-normalization-and-publish-database-integration",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Apply this skill after spreadOut() has converted raw CSV peak data into a structured list",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:28:17.596843+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/chemical-name-normalization-and-publish-database-integration/013",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The substructure information generated using ChemmineR includes the number of rings, all subgroups (e.g., R-COH, R-COOH, etc.) and their counts, all atoms (e.g., C, N, S, As, etc.) and their counts, and the number of charges for every chemical with published structural data",
      "asbval:note": "Ring count and functional groups are confirmed. Database membership filtering (LOTUS, KEGG, FEMA, FDA/SPL) is confirmed in categorate() function.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "chemical-name-normalization-and-publish-database-integration",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Use it when downstream analysis requires chemical subsetting by molecular weight, ring count, functional groups, or membership in curated databases (LOTUS, KEGG, FEMA, FDA/SPL)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:28:17.596843+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/chemical-structure-similarity-matching/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The 'categorate()' function will then take the input library (saved as a \".CSV\") and compare every chemical of interest to the chemicals in each user-defined \"chemical category,\" returning two additional data frames\u2014(1) whether it has a strong (Tanimoto similarity greater than 0.95) or moderate (greater than 0.85) structural match with any of the chemicals in each group; and, (2) for strong matches, the name of a chemical that it was most similar to. It performs these comparisons using the \"fmcsBatch()\" function from the R package fmcsR.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper explicitly describes FMCS-based structural matching with 0.95 threshold for strong matches and 0.85 for moderate matches, matching the card's description.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "chemical-structure-similarity-matching",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "A cheminformatics skill that uses structural fingerprinting and maximum common substructure (FMCS) algorithms to identify and rank structurally similar compounds within a chemical library. It quantifies structural similarity via match scores (typically \u22650.95 threshold) to enable ",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:28:40.589775+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/chemical-structure-similarity-matching/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "For the chemical structure processing, our package utilizes Tanimoto similarity, a commonly used and rigorously tested metric for physicochemical comparisons. ... The substructure information generated using ChemmineR includes the number of rings, all subgroups (e.g., R-COH, R-COOH, etc.) and their counts, all atoms (e.g., C, N, S, As, etc.) and their counts, and the number of charges for every chemical with published structural data (or canonical SMILES from CACTUS) on PubChem.",
      "asbval:note": "ChemmineR is confirmed as a dependency used for structural fingerprinting and substructure analysis.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "chemical-structure-similarity-matching",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "ChemmineR \u2014 Computes structural fingerprints and similarity metrics for query and library chemicals",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:28:40.589775+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/chemical-structure-similarity-matching/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "It performs these comparisons using the \"fmcsBatch()\" function from the R package fmcsR [34].",
      "asbval:note": "fmcsR is explicitly named and used for FMCS-based structural matching via fmcsBatch().",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "chemical-structure-similarity-matching",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "fmcsR \u2014 Calculates maximum common substructure (FMCS) overlap and atomic feature descriptors",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:28:40.589775+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/chemical-structure-similarity-matching/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To collect these data, the function converts the chemical names into PubChem compound identifiers (CIDs) using the \"get_cid()\" function from the R package webchem [32].",
      "asbval:note": "webchem is confirmed for chemical name resolution to PubChem CIDs. External database integration (LOTUS, KEGG, FEMA, FDA/SPL) is confirmed in passage 5 for categorate() function.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "chemical-structure-similarity-matching",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "webchem \u2014 Resolves chemical names to structure data and integrates external database lookups (PubChem, LOTUS, KEGG, FEMA, FDA/SPL)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:28:40.589775+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/chemical-structure-similarity-matching/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The next step in the GC-MS workflow will depend on the type of analysis the user is performing. ... Another approach could include subsetting with output from the function \"categorate()\". This function also uses PubChem to communicate with online databases and generate categorically, structurally, and chemically identifying information for every published chemical in the dataset.",
      "asbval:note": "categorate() is confirmed to orchestrate structural matching and output structural similarity results, but the paper does not use the term 'BestChemMatch' \u2014 it returns data frames with Tanimoto similarity scores and matched chemical names.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "chemical-structure-similarity-matching",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "uafR::categorate \u2014 Orchestrates structural matching across cheminformatics packages and outputs BestChemMatch results",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:28:40.589775+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/chemical-structure-similarity-matching/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Subsetting of information generated with \"categorate()\" is easily done using the function\u2013\"exactoThese()\". Users can specify which set of information they would like to subset and indicate desired criteria the chemicals should meet.",
      "asbval:note": "exactoThese() is confirmed as a subsetting function for categorate() output with customizable criteria.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "chemical-structure-similarity-matching",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "uafR::exactoThese \u2014 Subsets categorate() output by database presence, FMCS properties (MW, rings, groups, atoms, charges), or library groups",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
