    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/chemical-structure-similarity-matching/007",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The first dataset on which uafR functions were tested was a series of standards including, ethyl hexanoate (Prod#14896, CAS#123-66-0, Millipore Sigma, Burlington, MA, USA), methyl salicylate (Prod#M6752, CAS#119-36-8, Millipore Sigma)",
      "asbval:note": "The paper uses ethyl hexanoate and methyl salicylate as test compounds, confirming the scope example.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "chemical-structure-similarity-matching",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "When you have a set of query chemicals (e.g., ethyl hexanoate, methyl salicylate) and need to find their best-matched structural analogues within a reference library",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:28:40.589775+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/chemical-structure-similarity-matching/008",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "A simple and effective approach is to subset the search chemicals by setting a minimal match factor on the raw output of Unknowns Analysis (or other GC-MS software). ... Another approach could include subsetting with output from the function \"categorate()\". ... For chemistry, structure defines function, so identifying structural matches is effectively identifying chemicals with the same function.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper describes categorate() as an alternative to simple Match.Factor filtering, using structural similarity for deeper chemical classification.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "chemical-structure-similarity-matching",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Use this when Match.Factor filtering alone is insufficient and you need to confirm structural relationships beyond retention time and m/z matching.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:28:40.589775+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/cheminformatics-library-querying/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The categorical data include whether the chemical is biologically derived [Natural Products Online database (LOTUS; https://lotus.naturalproducts.net/)], has flavor or smell [Flavor and Extract Manufacturers Association (FEMA; https://www.femaflavor.org/)], has varied biological activities [Kyoto Encyclopedia of Genes and Genomes (KEGG; https://www.genome.jp/kegg/)], medical subject headings (MeSH; https://www.nlm.nih.gov/mesh/), or other information about their reactivity [Food and Drug Administration\u2014Structured Product Labeling (FDA/SPL; https://www.fda.gov/) and Reactive Groups from PubChem (https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/)].",
      "asbval:note": "Fully supported. Paper describes querying chemical libraries against compounds to retrieve categorical metadata from multiple external databases including PubChem, LOTUS, KEGG, FEMA, and FDA/SPL.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "cheminformatics-library-querying",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Query a structured chemical library against a set of query compounds to retrieve categorical metadata, structural similarity scores, and database presence flags using cheminformatics packages. This skill enables systematic identification of compounds matching specific structural ",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:28:59.058100+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/cheminformatics-library-querying/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "For the chemical structure processing, our package utilizes Tanimoto similarity, a commonly used and rigorously tested metric for physicochemical comparisons... The substructure information generated using ChemmineR includes the number of rings, all subgroups (e.g., R-COH, R-COOH, etc.) and their counts, all atoms (e.g., C, N, S, As, etc.) and their counts, and the number of charges for every chemical with published structural data (or canonical SMILES from CACTUS) on PubChem.",
      "asbval:note": "Confirmed. ChemmineR is used for structure comparison and substructure analysis.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "cheminformatics-library-querying",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "ChemmineR - Provides cheminformatics infrastructure for structure comparison, similarity scoring, and compound object manipulation",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:28:59.058100+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/cheminformatics-library-querying/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "It performs these comparisons using the \"fmcsBatch()\" function from the R package fmcsR [34].",
      "asbval:note": "Confirmed. fmcsR is used for structural similarity comparisons via fmcsBatch() function.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "cheminformatics-library-querying",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "fmcsR - Computes maximum common substructure (FMCS) matching and structural similarity scores between query and library compounds",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:28:59.058100+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/cheminformatics-library-querying/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To collect these data, the function converts the chemical names into PubChem compound identifiers (CIDs) using the \"get_cid()\" function from the R package webchem [32].",
      "asbval:note": "Confirmed. webchem is used to resolve chemical names to PubChem identifiers and query external databases.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "cheminformatics-library-querying",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "webchem - Resolves chemical names to structures and queries external databases (PubChem, LOTUS, KEGG, FEMA, FDA/SPL) for categorical metadata",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:28:59.058100+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/cheminformatics-library-querying/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The next step in the GC-MS workflow will depend on the type of analysis the user is performing... There are multiple steps that can be taken to hone in on the most relevant chemicals in a dataset using the features of uafR... Another approach could include subsetting with output from the function \"categorate()\"... Subsetting of information generated with \"categorate()\" is easily done using the function\u2013\"exactoThese()\".",
      "asbval:note": "Confirmed. uafR package contains categorate() and exactoThese() functions for cheminformatics integration.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "cheminformatics-library-querying",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "uafR - R package wrapping categorate(), exactoThese(), and associated workflow functions for mass spectrometry and cheminformatics integration",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:28:59.058100+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/cheminformatics-library-querying/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "We have developed an R package, uafR, that automates a grueling retrieval process for gas-chromatography coupled mass spectrometry (GC-MS) data... Our streamlined cheminformatics workflows allow anyone with basic experience in R to pull out component areas for tentative compound identifications.",
      "asbval:note": "Confirmed. R is the primary language for the cheminformatics workflows described.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "cheminformatics-library-querying",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "R - general programming language for cheminformatics workflows",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:28:59.058100+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/cheminformatics-library-querying/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The \"categorate()\" function will then take the input library (saved as a \".CSV\") and compare every chemical of interest to the chemicals in each user-defined \"chemical category,\" returning two additional data frames\u2014(1) whether it has a strong (Tanimoto similarity greater than 0.95) or moderate (greater than 0.85) structural match with any of the chemicals in each group; and, (2) for strong matches, the name of a chemical that it was most similar to.",
      "asbval:note": "Fully supported. The paper describes querying libraries against compounds to retrieve structural similarity scores and categorical metadata.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "cheminformatics-library-querying",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Query a structured chemical library against a set of query compounds to retrieve categorical metadata, structural similarity scores, and database presence flags",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:28:59.058100+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/cheminformatics-library-querying/007",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The categorical data include whether the chemical is biologically derived [Natural Products Online database (LOTUS)]... has flavor or smell [Flavor and Extract Manufacturers Association (FEMA)]... has varied biological activities [Kyoto Encyclopedia of Genes and Genomes (KEGG)]... or other information about their reactivity [Food and Drug Administration\u2014Structured Product Labeling (FDA/SPL) and Reactive Groups from PubChem].",
      "asbval:note": "Fully supported. Paper describes systematic querying across multiple external databases.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "cheminformatics-library-querying",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Systematic identification of compounds matching specific structural or property criteria across multiple external databases",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:28:59.058100+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/chromatographic-retention-time-matching/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "After identifying perfect matches (i.e., those with high match factors and the same chemical names) the algorithm looks again through each sample for instances where the top 2 published m/z values for the tentative identity are the same as the query chemicals of interest... The m/z values within retention time windows generated by the input data must be similar enough that the chemical fragments are practically and theoretically identical.",
      "asbval:note": "Core functionality of mzExacto() confirmed: uses retention time windows and published m/z values to match query chemicals.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "chromatographic-retention-time-matching",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "A GC-MS data processing skill that uses retention time (RT) and published m/z peaks to precisely identify and match query chemicals within preprocessed mass spectrometry datasets.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:29:14.771488+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/chromatographic-retention-time-matching/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "\"mzExacto()\" takes the output from \"spreadOut()\" along with the list of chemical names, and returns a single data frame containing their optimal retention time, exact mass, best identified match factor, and aggregated component area across samples in which it occurs (0 when absent).",
      "asbval:note": "Aggregation across samples explicitly confirmed.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "chromatographic-retention-time-matching",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "This skill enables unambiguous chemical identification by aggregating multiple detection instances across samples that share matching retention times and mass spectral signatures.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:29:14.771488+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/chromatographic-retention-time-matching/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The first function for GC -MS data is \"spreadOut()\". Running this function on properly formatted GC -MS input will automatically prepare the data for the next steps in the processing pipeline.",
      "asbval:note": "Function name and role confirmed.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "chromatographic-retention-time-matching",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "spreadOut function from uafR package",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:29:14.771488+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/chromatographic-retention-time-matching/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Briefly, the function takes every recorded data point for every treatment and expands it in large database formats with unique identifiers assigned for each data point... In addition to setting up large databases containing component area, tentative compound identities, match factors, captured m/z values, retention time indices, sample identities, and the unique IDs, the function also communicates with online databases to download relevant information about every tentative compound.",
      "asbval:note": "Confirmed: organizes retention times, m/z values, and other metadata into structured format.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "chromatographic-retention-time-matching",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "spreadOut converts raw .CSV input into structured spread dictionary format with organized retention times and published masses",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:29:14.771488+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/chromatographic-retention-time-matching/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "If the chemicals of interest are already known, they can be extracted by name with a single function\u2014\"mzExacto()\".",
      "asbval:note": "Function name and basic role confirmed.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "chromatographic-retention-time-matching",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "mzExacto function from uafR package",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:29:14.771488+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/chromatographic-retention-time-matching/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "\"mzExacto()\" takes the output from \"spreadOut()\" along with the list of chemical names, and returns a single data frame containing their optimal retention time, exact mass, best identified match factor, and aggregated component area across samples in which it occurs (0 when absent)... Briefly, after collecting mass and m/z information for the input chemicals of interest, they are ordered by exact masses so likely retention time windows can be determined based on the general structure of the input data and the information stored from \"spreadOut()\". After identifying perfect matches (i.e., those with high match factors and the same chemical names) the algorithm looks again through each sample for instances where the top 2 published m/z values for the tentative identity are the same as the query chemicals of interest.",
      "asbval:note": "Confirmed: uses retention time windows and m/z matching to aggregate across samples.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "chromatographic-retention-time-matching",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "mzExacto searches the spread dictionary using retention time and m/z peak matching to extract and aggregate all instances of query chemicals across samples",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:29:14.771488+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/chromatographic-retention-time-matching/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "We have developed an R package, uafR, that automates a grueling retrieval process for gas -chromatography coupled mass spectrometry (GC -MS) data",
