      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/functional-group-classification/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The categorical data include whether the chemical is biologically derived [Natural Products Online database (LOTUS; https://lotus.naturalproducts.net/)], has flavor or smell [Flavor and Extract Manufacturers Association (FEMA; https://www.femaflavor.org/)], has varied biological activities [Kyoto Encyclopedia of Genes and Genomes (KEGG; https://www.genome.jp/kegg/)], medical subject headings (MeSH; https://www.nlm.nih.gov/mesh/), or other information about their reactivity [Food and Drug Administration\u2014Structured Product Labeling (FDA/SPL; https://www.fda.gov/) and Reactive Groups from PubChem (https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/)]. After the categorical information is collected, the function generates substructure data for the chemicals to also be subsetted by common functional groups. This information is generated using the \"read.SDFset()\" function from another R package called ChemmineR [33]. This package is a dependency that is installed with uafR and is core to the cheminformatics methods deployed. The substructure information generated using ChemmineR includes the number of rings, all subgroups (e.g., R-COH, R-COOH, etc.) and their counts, all atoms (e.g., C, N, S, As, etc.) and their counts, and the number of charges for every chemical with published structural data (or canonical SMILES from CACTUS) on PubChem.",
      "asbval:note": "Claim is fully supported by passage describing categorate() function and its use of ChemmineR for structural analysis including rings, atoms, and functional groups.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "functional-group-classification",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Classify query chemicals into categorical groups based on structural and functional properties using cheminformatics packages that assess atomic features, ring systems, and molecular weight.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:30:21.946037+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/functional-group-classification/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "This information is generated using the \"read.SDFset()\" function from another R package called ChemmineR [33]. This package is a dependency that is installed with uafR and is core to the cheminformatics methods deployed. The substructure information generated using ChemmineR includes the number of rings, all subgroups (e.g., R-COH, R-COOH, etc.) and their counts, all atoms (e.g., C, N, S, As, etc.) and their counts, and the number of charges for every chemical with published structural data (or canonical SMILES from CACTUS) on PubChem.",
      "asbval:note": "ChemmineR is confirmed as a core dependency for structural analysis and substructure information generation.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "functional-group-classification",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "ChemmineR - Performs structural comparison and similarity assessment against chemical library groups",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:30:21.946037+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/functional-group-classification/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "It performs these comparisons using the \"fmcsBatch()\" function from the R package fmcsR [34].",
      "asbval:note": "fmcsR is confirmed as used for structural comparisons via fmcsBatch() function. The card's description of FMCS and atomic feature extraction is semantically consistent with the paper's use of fmcsR for structural matching in the categorate() workflow.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "functional-group-classification",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "fmcsR - Computes flexible maximum common substructure (FMCS) for structural matching and extracts atomic features (rings, groups, atoms, charges)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:30:21.946037+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/functional-group-classification/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To collect these data, the function converts the chemical names into PubChem compound identifiers (CIDs) using the \"get_cid()\" function from the R package webchem [32].",
      "asbval:note": "webchem is confirmed as used to query PubChem via get_cid() function. The paper also describes categorate() function using PubChem to communicate with online databases (LOTUS, KEGG, FEMA, FDA/SPL, MeSH), which aligns with the card's claim about querying external databases.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "functional-group-classification",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "webchem - Queries external chemical databases (PubChem, LOTUS, KEGG, FEMA, FDA/SPL) to retrieve categorical and regulatory information",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:30:21.946037+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/functional-group-classification/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The next step in the GC-MS workflow will depend on the type of analysis the user is performing. If the chemicals of interest are already known, they can be extracted by name with a single function\u2014\"mzExacto()\". However, for complex datasets or analyses that involve more unknowns, the user may want to cast a broader, but still accurate, net. There are multiple steps that can be taken to hone in on the most relevant chemicals in a dataset using the features of uafR. A simple and effective approach is to subset the search chemicals by setting a minimal match factor on the raw output of Unknowns Analysis (or other GC -MS software). This can be done with R code described in the vignette published with the package (https://castratton.github.io/uafR/). Another approach could include subsetting with output from the function \"categorate()\". This function also uses PubChem to communicate with online databases and generate categorically, structurally, and chemically identifying information for every published chemical in the dataset... Subsetting of information generated with \"categorate()\" is easily done using the function\u2013\"exactoThese()\".",
      "asbval:note": "uafR is confirmed as the R package providing both categorate() and exactoThese() functions for classification and filtering workflows.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "functional-group-classification",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "uafR - R package providing categorate() and exactoThese() functions to orchestrate functional group classification and filtering workflows",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:30:21.946037+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/functional-group-classification/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "We have developed an R package, uafR, that automates a grueling retrieval process for gas -chromatography coupled mass spectrometry (GC -MS) data and allows anyone interested in chemical comparisons to quickly perform advanced structural similarity matches. Our streamlined cheminformatics workflows allow anyone with basic experience in R to pull out component areas for tentative compound identifications using the best published understanding of molecules across samples (pubchem.gov).",
      "asbval:note": "R is confirmed as the programming language for the cheminformatics workflows described in the paper.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "functional-group-classification",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "R - programming language for cheminformatics workflows",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:30:21.946037+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
