    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/functional-group-classification/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "For example, if a researcher has a set of plant chemicals of interest to test against active ingredients in pharmaceuticals, the input library could contain n columns whose headings are the biological activity (e.g., diuretic, blood pressure, etc.) and the contents (rows under the heading) are the active chemicals used in products that are approved for those medical outcomes. The \"categorate()\" function will then take the input library (saved as a \".CSV\") and compare every chemical of interest to the chemicals in each user-defined \"chemical category,\" returning two additional data frames\u2014(1) whether it has a strong (Tanimoto similarity greater than 0.95) or moderate (greater than 0.85) structural match with any of the chemicals in each group; and, (2) for strong matches, the name of a chemical that it was most similar to.",
      "asbval:note": "The scope description is fully supported by the paper's description of categorate() function workflow for matching query chemicals against reference library groups.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "functional-group-classification",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Apply this skill when you have a set of query chemicals (chemical names or structures) and need to match them against a reference chemical library organized by type or category, with the goal of identifying structural similarity, functional group membership, or categorical assign",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
