    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/retention-time-and-mass-sorting-of-chromatographic-peaks/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "For the chemical structure processing, our package utilizes Tanimoto similarity... The substructure information generated using ChemmineR includes the number of rings, all subgroups (e.g., R-COH, R-COOH, etc.) and their counts, all atoms (e.g., C, N, S, As, etc.) and their counts, and the number of charges for every chemical with published structural data (or canonical SMILES from CACTUS) on PubChem. This information is generated using the \"read.SDFset()\" function from another R package called ChemmineR [33]. This package is a dependency that is installed with uafR and is core to the cheminformatics methods deployed.",
      "asbval:note": "ChemmineR is confirmed as a dependency for cheminformatics structure-based filtering.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "retention-time-and-mass-sorting-of-chromatographic-peaks",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "ChemmineR \u2014 cheminformatics package for structure-based queries and filtering of aggregated compounds",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:32:17.350612+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/retention-time-and-mass-sorting-of-chromatographic-peaks/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "It performs these comparisons using the \"fmcsBatch()\" function from the R package fmcsR [34]. The utility of this information and approach cannot be overstated. For chemistry, structure defines function, so identifying structural matches is effectively identifying chemicals with the same function.",
      "asbval:note": "fmcsR is confirmed as used for structural comparisons in the categorate() function (which feeds into exactoThese()).",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "retention-time-and-mass-sorting-of-chromatographic-peaks",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "fmcsR \u2014 molecular flexible common substructure comparisons; used in exactoThese() to subset by structural features (rings, groups, atoms, charges)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:32:17.350612+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/retention-time-and-mass-sorting-of-chromatographic-peaks/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To collect these data, the function converts the chemical names into PubChem compound identifiers (CIDs) using the \"get_cid()\" function from the R package webchem [32]. For published chemicals, this information includes exact mass, m/z histograms, and every name it has.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms webchem retrieves exact masses and synonyms from PubChem via get_cid(), but does not explicitly mention 'literature retention times' or 'ChemSpider' as sources. The claim about retention times and ChemSpider is not directly supported in the passages.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "retention-time-and-mass-sorting-of-chromatographic-peaks",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "webchem \u2014 retrieves exact masses, synonyms, and literature retention times from PubChem and ChemSpider; populates webInfo nested lists",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:32:17.350612+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/retention-time-and-mass-sorting-of-chromatographic-peaks/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Our R package harnesses direct connections between PubChem and R to stream published information on every known (i.e., published and vetted by peer-review for merit) chemical in the dataset... To collect these data, the function converts the chemical names into PubChem compound identifiers (CIDs) using the \"get_cid()\" function from the R package webchem [32]. For published chemicals, this information includes exact mass, m/z histograms, and every name it has.",
      "asbval:note": "PubChem is confirmed as the source for exact masses, chemical names/synonyms, and structure data.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "retention-time-and-mass-sorting-of-chromatographic-peaks",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "PubChem \u2014 source for exact monoisotopic masses, published chemical names (synonyms), and structure data",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:32:17.350612+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/retention-time-and-mass-sorting-of-chromatographic-peaks/007",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The current build of uafR is optimized for raw output from Agilent's Unknowns Analysis Software (Santa Clara, CA, USA, 95051); however, the only aspect of the workflow that is specific to their software are the column names for the input data frame.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms that column names are critical and specific to Agilent output; missing or misnamed columns would require pre-processing.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "retention-time-and-mass-sorting-of-chromatographic-peaks",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Input CSV is missing required column names (Component.RT, Base.Peak.MZ, Component.Area, Compound.Name, Match.Factor, File.Name) \u2014 pre-processing or column renaming is needed first.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:32:17.350612+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/retention-time-and-mass-sorting-of-chromatographic-peaks/008",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The next step in the GC-MS workflow will depend on the type of analysis the user is performing. If the chemicals of interest are already known, they can be extracted by name with a single function\u2014\"mzExacto()\". However, for complex datasets or analyses that involve more unknowns, the user may want to cast a broader, but still accurate, net.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper indicates that spreadOut() is the first step and subsequent functions (mzExacto, categorate, etc.) operate on its output, implying that re-running spreadOut on already-processed data would be redundant.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "retention-time-and-mass-sorting-of-chromatographic-peaks",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Data is already in a structured, deduplicated format (e.g., already converted by spreadOut or another peak-matching tool) \u2014 applying again risks redundant aggregation",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:32:17.350612+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/spectral-library-matching-and-m-z-peak-ranking/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The traditional methods involve manually selecting, integrating, and identifying peaks based on a reference library and comparison to commercial standards across every sample in an experiment. Software that quickly and accurately identify top library matches for every tentative compound in an entire batch of experimental samples thankfully exist (e.g. Agilent's MassHunter, Thermo Fisher Scientific's Compound Discoverer, Shimadzu's GCMSsolution); however, the output remains uninterpretable without additional process.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper describes matching peaks against reference libraries and using match factors; the card's framing of 'ranking' by match factor and m/z accuracy aligns with the paper's workflow.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "spectral-library-matching-and-m-z-peak-ranking",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Identify and rank chemical compounds in GC-MS data by matching observed mass spectra against published libraries and prioritizing peaks by match factor and m/z accuracy.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:32:39.606948+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/spectral-library-matching-and-m-z-peak-ranking/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The current build of uafR is optimized for raw output from Agilent's Unknowns Analysis Software (Santa Clara, CA, USA, 95051); however, the only aspect of the workflow that is specific to their software are the column names for the input data frame. To briefly describe the output, after setting up the analysis environment [i.e., directing Unknowns Analysis to the sample directory where a '.UAF' file (hence, uafR) is created], running the deconvolution algorithm to identify peaks, and searching the peaks against the installed library (blank subtraction and target matching are also options and will not affect the input for uafR), a single '.CSV' file containing basic GC -MS output [i.e. retention times, peak area, captured mass-to-charge ratios (m/z), compound name, match quality]",
      "asbval:note": "Paper explicitly states uafR processes Agilent Unknowns Analysis CSV output containing match quality and m/z data.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "spectral-library-matching-and-m-z-peak-ranking",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "converts raw Agilent Unknowns Analysis output into a structured, ranked list of candidate identifications suitable for downstream cheminformatic filtering",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:32:39.606948+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/spectral-library-matching-and-m-z-peak-ranking/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "We have developed an R package, uafR, that automates a grueling retrieval process for gas -chromatography coupled mass spectrometry (GC -MS) data",
      "asbval:note": "uafR is an R package; R is the host language.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "spectral-library-matching-and-m-z-peak-ranking",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "R (Host language for executing spreadOut() function and constructing output matrices)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:32:39.606948+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/spectral-library-matching-and-m-z-peak-ranking/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The current build of uafR is optimized for raw output from Agilent's Unknowns Analysis Software (Santa Clara, CA, USA, 95051)",
      "asbval:note": "Explicitly named as the source software for raw CSV input.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "spectral-library-matching-and-m-z-peak-ranking",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Agilent Unknowns Analysis (Source software generating the raw CSV input with spectral match factors and peak metadata)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:32:39.606948+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/spectral-library-matching-and-m-z-peak-ranking/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "For the chemical structure processing, our package utilizes Tanimoto similarity, a commonly used and rigorously tested metric for physicochemical comparisons. This information is generated using the 'read.SDFset()' function from another R package called ChemmineR [33]. This package is a dependency that is installed with uafR and is core to the cheminformatics methods deployed.",
      "asbval:note": "ChemmineR is confirmed as a dependency for cheminformatic functions.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "spectral-library-matching-and-m-z-peak-ranking",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "ChemmineR (Provides cheminformatic functions for mass and structural comparison in downstream workflows)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:32:39.606948+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/spectral-library-matching-and-m-z-peak-ranking/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Our R package harnesses direct connections between PubChem and R to stream published information on every known (i.e., published and vetted by peer-review for merit) chemical in the dataset. This bypasses the need for other computer programs or coding environments to perform physicochemical comparisons and allows our algorithm to outperform any comparable utility for this stage of mass spectrometry data processing.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms PubChem integration but does not mention ChemSpider. Only PubChem is explicitly named as the source database.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "spectral-library-matching-and-m-z-peak-ranking",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "PubChem/ChemSpider (Source databases for exact masses and published chemical names incorporated into webInfo metadata)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:32:39.606948+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/spectral-library-matching-and-m-z-peak-ranking/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The first function for GC -MS data is 'spreadOut().' Running this function on properly formatted GC -MS input will automatically prepare the data for the next steps in the processing pipeline. [...] If the chemicals of interest are already known, they can be extracted by name with a single function\u2014'mzExacto().' [...] Another approach could include subsetting with output from the function 'categorate().' [...] Subsetting of information generated with 'categorate()' is easily done using the function\u2013'exactoThese()'.",
      "asbval:note": "All four functions are explicitly named and described in the paper.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "spectral-library-matching-and-m-z-peak-ranking",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "uafR (R package containing spreadOut(), mzExacto(), categorate(), and exactoThese() functions for GC-MS processing)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:32:39.606948+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/spectral-library-matching-and-m-z-peak-ranking/007",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "It performs these comparisons using the 'fmcsBatch()' function from the R package fmcsR [34].",
      "asbval:note": "fmcsR is mentioned in the paper but the evidence_span quote provided in the card does not appear verbatim in the passages. The paper does confirm fmcsR is used for structural comparisons via fmcsBatch().",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "spectral-library-matching-and-m-z-peak-ranking",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "fmcsR (evidence_spans: 'uafR taps into an amazing set of cheminformatics packages -- ChemmineR, fmcsR, webchem')",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:32:39.606948+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/spectral-library-matching-and-m-z-peak-ranking/008",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To collect these data, the function converts the chemical names into PubChem compound identifiers (CIDs) using the 'get_cid()' function from the R package webchem [32].",
      "asbval:note": "webchem is confirmed in the paper but the evidence_span quote provided in the card does not appear verbatim in the passages. The paper confirms webchem is used for CID conversion.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "spectral-library-matching-and-m-z-peak-ranking",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "webchem (evidence_spans: 'uafR taps into an amazing set of cheminformatics packages -- ChemmineR, fmcsR, webchem')",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
