      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:32:39.606948+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/spectral-library-matching-and-m-z-peak-ranking/012",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The next step in the GC-MS workflow will depend on the type of analysis the user is performing. If the chemicals of interest are already known, they can be extracted by name with a single function\u2014'mzExacto().' However, for complex datasets or analyses that involve more unknowns, the user may want to cast a broader, but still accurate, net. There are multiple steps that can be taken to hone in on the most relevant chemicals in a dataset using the features of uafR.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper describes the sequential workflow: spreadOut() first, then mzExacto() or categorate()/exactoThese() for subsetting.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "spectral-library-matching-and-m-z-peak-ranking",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "You need to subset or filter compounds before structural ranking \u2014 use spreadOut() first, then apply mzExacto() or exactoThese() on the output.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:32:39.606948+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/spectral-library-matching-validation/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "mzExacto() takes the output from spreadOut() along with the list of chemical names, and returns a single data frame containing their optimal retention time, exact mass, best identified match factor, and aggregated component area across samples in which it occurs... After identifying perfect matches (i.e., those with high match factors and the same chemical names) the algorithm looks again through each sample for instances where the top 2 published m/z values for the tentative identity are the same as the query chemicals of interest.",
      "asbval:note": "Core functionality of mzExacto() matches the research question exactly.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "spectral-library-matching-validation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Validate and extract mass spectrometry compound identifications by searching preprocessed spectral libraries for known query chemicals using retention time, m/z values, and match factor thresholds.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:33:06.634999+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/spectral-library-matching-validation/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "A sub-argument, 'decontaminate,' is on by default and removes any chemicals that did not have a strong match across samples, were unable to be found in public databases (i.e. PubChem), and/or were unable to have a canonical SMILES generated on the NCI server.",
      "asbval:note": "Quality filtering is built into mzExacto() via the decontaminate argument.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "spectral-library-matching-validation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "This skill ensures that retrieved compound metadata (m/z, RT, match factor, area) meets quality standards before downstream analysis.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:33:06.634999+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/spectral-library-matching-validation/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The first function for GC-MS data is 'spreadOut().' Running this function on properly formatted GC-MS input will automatically prepare the data for the next steps in the processing pipeline. Briefly, the function takes every recorded data point for every treatment and expands it in large database formats with unique identifiers assigned for each data point... In addition to setting up large databases containing component area, tentative compound identities, match factors, captured m/z values, retention time indices, sample identities, and the unique IDs, the function also communicates with online databases to download relevant information about every tentative compound.",
      "asbval:note": "Exact match to card description.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "spectral-library-matching-validation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "spreadOut: prepares raw GC-MS .CSV data into indexed dictionary structure with retention times, m/z, match factors, and area matrices for downstream spectral library searching",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:33:06.634999+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/spectral-library-matching-validation/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "mzExacto() takes the output from spreadOut() along with the list of chemical names, and returns a single data frame containing their optimal retention time, exact mass, best identified match factor, and aggregated component area across samples in which it occurs (0 when absent).",
      "asbval:note": "Exact match to card description.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "spectral-library-matching-validation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "mzExacto: searches preprocessed spread dictionary to extract and consolidate m/z, retention time, match factor, and area data for query chemicals across multiple samples",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:33:06.634999+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/spectral-library-matching-validation/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Subsetting of information generated with 'categorate()' is easily done using the function\u2013'exactoThese().' Users can specify which set of information they would like to subset and indicate desired criteria the chemicals should meet.",
      "asbval:note": "Function exists and is used for subsetting; however, the specific subsetting criteria (molecular weight, functional groups, ring count, database membership) are actually generated by categorate(), not exactoThese(). The card's description conflates the roles slightly.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "spectral-library-matching-validation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "exactoThese: subsets validated compound lists by chemical properties (molecular weight, functional groups, ring count) or database membership (LOTUS, FEMA, KEGG, FDA/SPL) after mzExacto returns results",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:33:06.634999+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/spectral-library-matching-validation/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The next step in the GC-MS workflow will depend on the type of analysis the user is performing... Another approach could include subsetting with output from the function 'categorate().' This function also uses PubChem to communicate with online databases and generate categorically, structurally, and chemically identifying information for every published chemical in the dataset. The categorical data include whether the chemical is biologically derived [Natural Products Online database (LOTUS; https://lotus.naturalproducts.net/)], has flavor or smell [Flavor and Extract Manufacturers Association (FEMA; https://www.femaflavor.org/)], has varied biological activities [Kyoto Encyclopedia of Genes and Genomes (KEGG; https://www.genome.jp/kegg/)], medical subject headings (MeSH; https://www.nlm.nih.gov/mesh/), or other information about their reactivity [Food and Drug Administration\u2014Structured Product Labeling (FDA/SPL; https://www.fda.gov/) and Reactive Groups from PubChem (https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/)]... The substructure information generated using ChemmineR includes the number of rings, all subgroups (e.g., R-COH, R-COOH, etc.) and their counts, all atoms (e.g., C, N, S, As, etc.) and their counts, and the number of charges for every chemical with published structural data (or canonical SMILES from CACTUS) on PubChem.",
      "asbval:note": "Exact match to card description.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "spectral-library-matching-validation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "categorate: enriches validated compounds with cheminformatics metadata (reactive groups, SMILES, molecular properties) and database cross-references for post-validation filtering",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:33:06.634999+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/spectral-library-matching-validation/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "We have developed an R package, uafR, that automates a grueling retrieval process for gas-chromatography coupled mass spectrometry (GC-MS) data",
      "asbval:note": "uafR is an R package; R is the execution environment.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "spectral-library-matching-validation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
