    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/structural-type-categorization/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "We have developed an R package, uafR, that automates a grueling retrieval process for gas-chromatography coupled mass spectrometry (GC-MS) data... The first function for GC-MS data is 'spreadOut().'... Next in the GC-MS workflow is to put the published information to use and aggregate every occurrence of the user-specified chemicals across every GC-MS sample. 'mzExacto()' takes the output from 'spreadOut()'... Subsetting of information generated with 'categorate()' is easily done using the function\u2013'exactoThese()'.",
      "asbval:note": "uafR confirmed as R package containing all named functions.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "structural-type-categorization",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "uafR - R package hosting categorate() and companion workflow functions (spreadOut, mzExacto, exactoThese)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:33:32.976906+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/structural-type-categorization/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "We have developed an R package, uafR... Our streamlined cheminformatics workflows allow anyone with basic experience in R to pull out component areas for tentative compound identifications... If the user can install a package and read a '.CSV' file into R, they will have access to the entirety of PubChem and more.",
      "asbval:note": "R is the core environment for uafR and all functions.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "structural-type-categorization",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "R - programming language/environment",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:33:32.976906+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/structural-type-categorization/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The 'categorate()' function will then take the input library (saved as a '.CSV') and compare every chemical of interest to the chemicals in each user-defined 'chemical category,' returning two additional data frames\u2014(1) whether it has a strong (Tanimoto similarity greater than 0.95) or moderate (greater than 0.85) structural match with any of the chemicals in each group; and, (2) for strong matches, the name of a chemical that it was most similar to.",
      "asbval:note": "Exact match to scope description: categorate() compares query chemicals to reference library groups and returns structural similarity scores.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "structural-type-categorization",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Categorizes query chemicals against a reference library by computing structural similarity scores and identifying best-matched compounds in each library group",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:33:32.976906+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/structural-type-categorization/007",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "In order to run 'categorate()', users are required to include an input library that contains columns with labeled chemicals. The labels are customizable, but the most useful approach is to label a set of chemicals by a common feature or biological activity. For example, if a researcher has a set of plant chemicals of interest to test against active ingredients in pharmaceuticals, the input library could contain n columns whose headings are the biological activity (e.g., diuretic, blood pressure, etc.) and the contents (rows under the heading) are the active chemicals used in products that are approved for those medical outcomes.",
      "asbval:note": "Confirms use case with named groups and query chemicals.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "structural-type-categorization",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "When to use: when you have a set of query chemical compounds (by name or SMILES) and a reference library organized into named groups",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:33:32.976906+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/structural-type-categorization/008",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Instances where the chemical cannot be identified by name on PubChem (i.e. compounds for which a CID are unavailable) are redirected to CADD Group Chemoinformatics Tools and User Services (CACTUS, https://cactus.nci.nih.gov/) from which a canonical Simplified Molecular Input Line Entry System (SMILES) can be generated using that server and algorithm... A sub-argument, 'decontaminate,' is on by default and removes any chemicals that did not have a strong match across samples, were unable to be found in public databases (i.e. PubChem), and/or were unable to have a canonical SMILES generated on the NCI server.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms that chemicals without resolvable names/SMILES are problematic and removed by decontaminate function.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "structural-type-categorization",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "When NOT to use: Query chemicals lack SMILES or canonical names resolvable by PubChem/webchem",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:33:32.976906+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/summary-statistics-table-construction/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "A simple and effective approach is to subset the search chemicals by setting a minimal match factor on the raw output of Unknowns Analysis (or other GC -MS software)... After analyzing the samples on the GC-MS, the raw output is saved to a local directory and loaded into Unknowns Analysis following default protocols... Each peak was then searched against the NIST 20 database. The aggregated data frame was exported as a \".CSV\" file. This data frame included columns for the compound names (\"Compound.Name\"), file name the tentative identity is from (\"File.Name\"), top m/z peaks captured by the GC/MS (\"Base.Peak.MZ\"), match factors for tentative identities (\"Match.Factor\"), and retention times (\"Component.RT\").",
      "asbval:note": "The paper explicitly demonstrates filtering by Match.Factor thresholds (>65%, >75%, >88.9, >97.2) and presents results in Table 1 showing how compound counts and statistical outcomes vary across these filter conditions.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "summary-statistics-table-construction",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Construct a summary table that aggregates counts or statistics across multiple filter conditions applied to a compound dataset. This skill is used to compare how data volume changes when different threshold criteria are applied to mass spectrometry results.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:33:55.685223+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/summary-statistics-table-construction/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "We have developed an R package, uafR, that automates a grueling retrieval process for gas -chromatography coupled mass spectrometry (GC -MS) data... If the user can install a package and read a \".CSV\" file into R, they will have access to the entirety of PubChem and more.",
      "asbval:note": "R is the primary language and environment for the entire workflow, including loading CSV files and constructing summary tables.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
