    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/unique-compound-enumeration/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "A simple and effective approach is to subset the search chemicals by setting a minimal match factor on the raw output of Unknowns Analysis (or other GC -MS software)... After identifying perfect matches (i.e., those with high match factors and the same chemical names) the algorithm looks again through each sample for instances where the top 2 published m/z values for the tentative identity are the same as the query chemicals of interest.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper explicitly describes subsetting by match factor thresholds and demonstrates this in Table 1 with multiple match factor cutoffs (>65%, >75%, >88.9%, >97.2%), showing compound counts at each threshold level.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "unique-compound-enumeration",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Enumerate and count unique chemical compounds in a mass spectrometry dataset after applying quality-based filtering thresholds. This skill isolates high-confidence identifications from GC-MS outputs by retaining only compounds that meet specified Match.Factor criteria, enabling c",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:34:12.878953+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/unique-compound-enumeration/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "We have developed an R package, uafR, that automates a grueling retrieval process for gas-chromatography coupled mass spectrometry (GC-MS) data... If the user can install a package and read a '.CSV' file into R, they will have access to the entirety of PubChem and more.",
      "asbval:note": "R is the primary language for the uafR package and all workflows described.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "unique-compound-enumeration",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "R",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:34:12.878953+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/unique-compound-enumeration/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "[SUBSTRING-MATCH for uafR | role: R package providing spreadOut() and mzExacto() functions]. The package here comes after the initial processing of samples and communicates with public chemistry utilities (including PubChem and the National Cancer Institute) to sort and process the aggregated set of all tentatively identified molecules using underlying m/z (mass/charge of chemical fragments) ratio data and automatically interpret close matches across samples.",
      "asbval:note": "uafR is confirmed as the R package with spreadOut() and mzExacto() functions for GC-MS data processing.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "unique-compound-enumeration",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "uafR",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:34:12.878953+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/unique-compound-enumeration/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "It can be downloaded for free along with sample datasets from Github at github.org/castratton/uafR or installed directly from R or RStudio using the developer tools: 'devtools::install_github(\"castratton/uafR\")'.",
      "asbval:note": "Repository URL confirmed (note: paper uses github.org but standard is github.com; both resolve to the same repository).",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "unique-compound-enumeration",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools[uafR].repo",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "https://github.com/castratton/uafR",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:34:12.878953+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/unique-compound-enumeration/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The first function for GC-MS data is 'spreadOut().' Running this function on properly formatted GC-MS input will automatically prepare the data for the next steps in the processing pipeline... Next in the GC-MS workflow is to put the published information to use and aggregate every occurrence of the user-specified chemicals across every GC-MS sample. 'mzExacto()' takes the output from 'spreadOut()' along with the list of chemical names, and returns a single data frame containing their optimal retention time, exact mass, best identified match factor, and aggregated component area across samples in which it occurs.",
      "asbval:note": "Both functions are confirmed with their roles in data preparation and compound extraction.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "unique-compound-enumeration",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools[uafR].role",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "R package providing spreadOut() and mzExacto() functions to prepare and extract query chemicals from GC-MS datasets; integrates with this skill for filtered compound list handling",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:34:12.878953+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/unique-compound-enumeration/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Table 1 Summary of NMDS and ANOSIM calculation for models processed with uafR... >65% Match Factor... >75% Match Factor... >88.9 Match Factor... >97.2 Match Factor... # Compounds in Final Table 27, 16, 0, a",
      "asbval:note": "Table 1 directly demonstrates enumeration of compounds at multiple Match Factor thresholds, showing the exact use case described in the card.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pone-0306202",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "unique-compound-enumeration",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Apply this skill when you have a GC-MS results table with a Match.Factor column (representing identification confidence) and you need to understand how many distinct compounds survive at different quality cutoffs (e.g., \u226565, \u226580, \u226590).",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:34:12.878953+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
